<subSubSection pageId="685" pageNumber="686" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="685" pageNumber="686">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bedel" authorityYear="1897" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Metophonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="685" pageNumber="686" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Metophonus</taxonomicName>
Bedel, 1897: 111. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1829" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Harpalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="685" pageNumber="686" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="syriacus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="685" pageNumber="686">Harpalus syriacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1829 by original designation. Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="685" pageNumber="686">meta</emphasis>
(between, among, beyond) and the generic name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1821" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Ophonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="685" pageNumber="686" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="685" pageNumber="686">Ophonus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="685" pageNumber="686">q.v</emphasis>
.] [masculine].
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="685" pageNumber="686">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schauberger" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Sulcophonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="685" pageNumber="686" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sulcophonus</taxonomicName>
Schauberger, 1933: 130. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tschitscherine" authorityYear="1902" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Harpalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="685" pageNumber="686" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sulcifer">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="685" pageNumber="686">Harpalus sulcifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tschitschérine">Tschitscherine</normalizedToken>
, 1902 (= 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reiche &amp; Saulcy" authorityYear="1855" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Ophonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="685" pageNumber="686" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cribrellus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="685" pageNumber="686">Ophonus cribrellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Reiche and Saulcy, 1855) by monotypy. Synonymy established by Sciaky (1987: 70). Etymology. From the Latin 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="685" pageNumber="686">sulcus</emphasis>
(furrow, groove) and the generic name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1821" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Ophonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="685" pageNumber="686" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="685" pageNumber="686">Ophonus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="685" pageNumber="686">q.v</emphasis>
.] [masculine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="685" pageNumber="686" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="685" pageNumber="686">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="685" pageNumber="686">
About 40 Palaearctic species, of which a single one, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tschitscherine" authorityYear="1893" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Ophonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="685" pageNumber="686" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stricticollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="685" pageNumber="686">Ophonus stricticollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tschitschérine">Tschitscherine</normalizedToken>
, is found in eastern Asia. Two species are adventive in eastern North America.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
